{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as a pressure gauge measuring the electrical 'push' in the wires.",
      "misconception": "Often incorrectly called a 'voltage meter'; the correct technical term is always voltmeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Like a flow-rate sensor on a water pipe, it measures how many electrons pass by per second.",
      "misconception": "Beginners sometimes think an ammeter measures voltage because they are used to seeing both on a multimeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure electrical resistance, which is the opposition to current flow.",
      "anchor": "Used to check how much a component 'fights' or resists the flow of electricity.",
      "misconception": "Confusing resistance measurement with continuity; while related, an ohmmeter provides a specific numerical value of opposition."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure electrical power, which is the rate at which energy is being used.",
      "anchor": "Shows the 'instantaneous' work being done, like the speedometer in a car showing current speed.",
      "misconception": "Confusing power (Watts) with energy (Joules/kWh). A wattmeter shows the rate, not the total amount used over time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument (often called a kilowatt-hour meter) that measures the total electrical energy consumed over time.",
      "anchor": "The meter found at the intake of a building used by electricity companies for billing.",
      "misconception": "Thinking a Wattmeter and an Energy Meter are the same; one measures the 'rate' (Power) while the other measures the 'total' (Energy)."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Voltmeter for voltage",
    "Ammeter for current",
    "Ohmmeter for resistance",
    "Wattmeter for power",
    "Energy meter for total consumption"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using the term 'voltage meter' instead of voltmeter",
    "Confusing instantaneous power with cumulative energy",
    "Believing an ammeter measures the electrical 'push' rather than the 'flow'"
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Measuring Voltage and Current",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure potential difference and the flow of electrons.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To measure the electrical 'push' or potential difference in a circuit, we use a Voltmeter. It is important to use the correct technical name; calling it a 'voltage meter' is non-standard in the electrical industry. A Voltmeter measures the difference in electrical pressure between two points in Volts (V).",
        "To measure the flow of electrons, known as current, we use an Ammeter. Think of the Ammeter like a flow-rate sensor on a water pipe—it measures how much electricity is passing through a specific point in Amperes (A). While modern multimeters can often perform both functions, you must identify the specific instrument by the quantity it is designed to measure. A Voltmeter measures voltage, and an Ammeter measures current."
      ],
      "hint": "Think of 'Volts' for the Voltmeter and 'Amps' for the Ammeter."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Measuring Resistance and Power",
      "objective": "Identify the instruments used to measure electrical opposition and the rate of doing work.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electrical resistance is the opposition that a material or component offers to the flow of current. To measure this opposition, we use an Ohmmeter. This device provides a specific numerical value in Ohms (Ω) to show how much a component 'fights' the flow of electricity. It is used to check the health of components like heating elements.",
        "Electrical power is the rate at which energy is being used at any single moment. To measure this instantaneous rate of work, we use a Wattmeter. It functions like the speedometer in a car, showing you the current rate of consumption in Watts (W). It does not measure the total amount used over a day, only the power being used at that exact second."
      ],
      "hint": "The Ohmmeter measures the 'Ohms' of resistance, while the Wattmeter measures the 'Watts' of power."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-3",
      "title": "Measuring Electrical Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the instrument used to measure the total energy consumed over time.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "While power is the rate of work, electrical energy is the total amount of work done over a duration of time. Because energy is cumulative, we cannot use a standard wattmeter to see the total usage over a month. Instead, we use an Energy Meter, which is also frequently called a kilowatt-hour (kWh) meter.",
        "The 'kWh' stands for Kilowatt-hour, which is the standard unit for billing. This is the instrument found at the service intake of a building. It tracks the total 'volume' of electricity consumed so that utility companies can charge for usage. It essentially adds up all the power used over every second the installation is active."
      ],
      "hint": "Energy is measured over time, so we use a meter that records kilowatt-hours (kWh)."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-4",
      "title": "Instrument Selection for AC2.3 Range",
      "objective": "Consolidate the mapping of all five core electrical quantities to their respective measuring instruments.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical industry, using precise names for instruments is a mark of professional competence. You must map each quantity to its specific meter. For potential difference, use a Voltmeter. For the flow of current, use an Ammeter. For the opposition to flow (resistance), use an Ohmmeter.",
        "For the instantaneous rate of doing work (power), use a Wattmeter. Finally, for the total consumption over time (energy), use an Energy Meter or kWh meter. Avoid using generic terms like 'tester' or 'meter' without the prefix, as each of these five quantities requires a specific measurement function to ensure accuracy and safety during circuit verification and fault finding."
      ],
      "hint": "Match the name of the unit (Volt, Amp, Ohm, Watt) to the start of the instrument name."
    }
  ]
}

